Class ExprMessage

  • java.lang.Object
    • ch.njol.skript.lang.util.SimpleExpression<java.lang.String>
      • ch.njol.skript.expressions.ExprMessage
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Debuggable, Expression<java.lang.String>, SyntaxElement

    @Name(value="Message")
@Description(value="The (chat) message of a chat event, the join message of a join event, the quit message of a quit event, or the death message on a death event. This expression is mostly useful for being changed.")
@Examples(value={"on chat:","\tplayer has permission \"admin\"","\tset message to \"%message%\"","","on first join:","\tset join message to \"Welcome %player% to our awesome server!\"","on join:","\tplayer has played before","\tset join message to \"Welcome back, %player%!\"","","on quit:","\tset quit message to \"%player% left this awesome server!\"","","on death:","\tset the death message to \"%player% died!\""})
@Since(value="1.4.6 (chat message), 1.4.9 (join & quit messages), 2.0 (death message)")
@Events(value={"chat","join","quit","death"})
public class ExprMessage
extends SimpleExpression<java.lang.String>

        matchedPattern - The index of the pattern which matched
        isDelayed - Whether this expression is used after a delay or not (i.e. if the event has already passed when this expression will be called)

      • acceptChange

        @Nullable
public java.lang.Class<?>[] acceptChange(Changer.ChangeMode mode)
        Description copied from interface: Expression
        Tests whether this expression supports the given mode, and if yes what type it expects the delta to be.

        Use ChangerUtils#acceptsChange(Expression, ChangeMode, Class...) to test whether an expression supports changing, don't directly use this method!

        Please note that if a changer is registered for this expression's returnType this method does not have to be overridden. If you override it though make sure to return super.acceptChange(mode), and to handle the appropriate ChangeMode(s) in #change(Event, Object[], ChangeMode) with super.change(...).

        Unlike Changer.acceptChange(ChangeMode) this method may print errors.

        Specified by:
        acceptChange in interface Expression<java.lang.String>
        Overrides:
        acceptChange in class SimpleExpression<java.lang.String>
        Returns:
        An array of types that #change(Event, Object[], ChangeMode) accepts as its delta parameter (which can be arrays to denote that multiple of that type are accepted), or null if the given mode is not supported. For Changer.ChangeMode.DELETE and Changer.ChangeMode.RESET this can return any non-null array to mark them as supported.
